<TITLE>Infrastructure design for Trades District ready for review</TITLE>
<TEXT>
Bloomington residents have a chance to look at the first phase of design proposals for the downtown Trades District The vision for the city s 12 acres in the Certified Technology Park are available to view inside City Hall until Feb 10 Principals with Indianapolis based Anderson Bohlander presented the designs to the Bloomington Redevelopment Commission earlier this month and left behind their renderings which are on easels in the atrium of City Hall Jon Bohlander a landscape architect and principal at the firm called the design for streets and other public areas the first foray into setting this new character and this new identity for the Trades District The design centers around specific themes with a focus of having an open and engaging space that is pedestrian focused but also harks back to the industrial use of the property which formerly was occupied by the historic Showers Brothers Furniture Co We really want it to be engaging Bohlander told members of the redevelopment commission We want the nature of the collaboration and the tech jobs to kind of spill over outside work hours Josh Anderson a landscape architect and urban designer who also is a principal with the firm emphasized elements the designers hope will contribute to that goal Most of the streets are designed with no curb and the streets generally are designed to be for pedestrian use There are wayfinding markers at key entry spaces and welcoming points including the B Line Trail and the space generally is open he said Commission members generally reacted positively to the visuals I think these are exciting Sue Sgambelluri said after the principals presentation The designs for this first phase of infrastructure improvements aren t yet completed With boards up in the atrium and designs also available at bloomington in gov trades along with a link to a survey for feedback the city and design team now have opened the feedback process up to the public The feedback period includes an open house from 5 to 7 p m Monday at City Hall 401 N Morton St which will serve as an informal opportunity for residents to meet with Mayor John Hamilton city staff and the Anderson Bohlander team to review design materials Hamilton said the presentation is a continuation of the community outreach efforts that resulted in the 2013 Certified Technology Park Master Plan and Redevelopment Strategy now that plans are more detailed and specific Our hope is to engage with the public as much as possible to keep the great work going said Alex Crowley who heads the city s Economic and Sustainable Development Department City staff will gather feedback from the open house online survey and other avenues at the end of the comment period Crowley said 
